Really nice recipe here. Honeysuckle and cream go together so well. The ice cream is very well balenced. I feel the honeysuckle is just a smidge too strong here though.&#xD;
&#xD;
Edit: after another week of steeping the honeysuckle has really mellowed out by the creams. Now this is absolutely perfect. Well done.

Fluffy clouds of summer. &#xD;
Close your eyes.&#xD;
Inhale.&#xD;
Now exhale. &#xD;
Think of walking down the street as a child, smelling the flowers.&#xD;
The ice cream truck's tinkling notes drift down the street.&#xD;
&#xD;
Right, now the silliness is over with, that is exactly what this juice made me feel. It reminded me of summers when I was a kid, grabbing an ice cream from the ice cream van with my mum and walking back with it in hand past our neighbour's garden and inhaling the strong scent of honeysuckle from the vines creeping up their house. &#xD;
The Vanilla is a background companion to the star of the show, the honeysuckle. I can see this being overpowering for people that don't usually like florals, but this was exactly what I hoped it would be. &#xD;
&#xD;
Beautiful.&#xD;

This is an amazing recipe.  The imagery, story, and profile work together flawlessly to create a mix that stimulates my palate and mind with its sweet, creamy, floral, ethereal, and elusive qualities.  ID1O-T has created a work of art by using all mediums at his disposal (i.e. words, images, flavor) to create a cathartic experience rather than just another faceless recipe.  &#xD;
&#xD;
The only reason I am giving four stars instead of five is because of the "elusive" part.  If I remove the back story and imagery (which I suspect most mixers will), and just focus on the mix itself, I am left with something that starts out incredible, but quickly looses flavor until you put it down for awhile and come back to it.  Maybe a longer steep will help with this (I waited 24 hours per the recipe's instructions).  Maybe ID10-T is well aware of this, and feels that this is essential to the whole "love lost" experience.  Who knows?  Anyway, thank you for sharing this.

